<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ads-google-reporting">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>ppc-manager</domain>
    <summary>Data-driven optimization cycle: monitor key metrics, analyze trends, diagnose root causes, and make targeted improvements via segment analysis and automated reporting.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>google-ads</tag>
      <tag>reporting</tag>
      <tag>optimization</tag>
      <tag>analytics</tag>
      <tag>metrics</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Google Ads Reporting &amp; Optimization</title>
    <summary>Google Ads data is abundant but insights are rare. Systematic reporting, segment analysis, metric diagnosis, and optimization cycles transform raw data into actionable improvements. This methodology teaches you how to read reports, diagnose issues, and optimize based on data rather than gut feeling.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Without a structured reporting and optimization process, campaigns drift. Daily gut-check optimization creates churn and resets learning. Competitors with data-driven processes win through compounded small wins: bid adjustments, negative keywords, landing page improvements, and audience refinement.</p>
      <p>A disciplined optimization cycle—monitor key metrics, analyze trends, diagnose root causes, implement targeted fixes—compounds over weeks and months. Each iteration refines your understanding of what drives conversions in your market, leading to lower CPA and higher ROAS.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Running continuous paid search campaigns and need a systematic weekly/monthly optimization process.</item>
        <item>Diagnosing performance drops: CPA increasing, impression share falling, or conversion rate declining.</item>
        <item>Building institutional knowledge: documenting what works in your market through repeated testing cycles.</item>
        <item>Multi-campaign management: prioritizing which campaigns and keywords deserve optimization effort first.</item>
        <item>Scaling spend: understanding which levers (bids, budgets, targeting) move the metrics that matter.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>New accounts with under 30 days history—algorithmic variance dominates treatment effect; wait for more data.</item>
        <item>Daily fluctuations—small day-to-day noise is normal; focus on weekly and monthly trends.</item>
        <item>Campaigns with fewer than 100 conversions per variant—insufficient data for diagnosis; ship the better option and move on.</item>
        <item>Holiday peaks (Black Friday, Q4)—exogenous demand swamps creative and targeting changes; use proven creatives instead.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="essential-reports">
      <p>Start with these core reports, each revealing different aspects of campaign health:</p>
      <p><term name="Overview">Dashboard view of high-level performance across all campaigns and key metrics.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Campaigns">Campaign-level metrics to identify which campaigns are over or under target.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Keywords">Keyword-level performance showing which keywords deliver conversions and which drain budget.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Search Terms">Actual searches triggering your keywords, revealing new negative keywords and keyword ideas.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Ads &amp; Assets">Ad and creative performance, showing which messaging resonates.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Auction Insights">Competitive positioning: your impression share vs. competitors and average positions.</term></p>
      <p>Add custom columns: Impressions, Clicks, CTR, Avg CPC, Cost, Conversions, Conv. rate, Cost/conv, Conv. value, ROAS, Quality Score, Impression share.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="key-metrics">
      <p>Each metric tells you something specific about campaign health:</p>
      <p><term name="Impressions">Your ad's reach potential. Low impressions suggest insufficient budget, narrow targeting, or low bids.</term></p>
      <p><term name="CTR">Click-through rate reflects ad relevance. Low CTR means ads don't match user intent; improve copy or landing page relevance.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Quality Score">Overall keyword health: Expected CTR + Ad relevance + Landing page experience. Score 7+ is healthy.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Conversion rate">Landing page effectiveness. Low conversion rate suggests offer mismatch, poor page experience, or targeting misalignment.</term></p>
      <p><term name="CPA">Cost per acquisition. If above target, reduce bids, improve quality, tighten targeting, or improve landing pages.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Impression share">Your market capture. Low impression share (below 80%) means missed opportunities; increase budget or bids.</term></p>
    </section>
    <section name="segment-analysis">
      <p>Segment your data to identify patterns and opportunities for targeted adjustments:</p>
      <p><term name="Device">Mobile vs. desktop performance often differs; adjust bids and landing pages per device.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Time">Day-of-week and hour-of-day patterns reveal when your audience converts; adjust bids for peak times.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Network">Search vs. Google Network (partner sites); often network traffic is higher-cost and lower-converting.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Location">Geographic performance varies; bid higher in high-converting regions, lower in low-converting ones.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Audience">Audience layer performance shows which audience segments convert best; adjust bids or exclusions accordingly.</term></p>
      <p>Process: add segment columns, identify best and worst performers, adjust bids by segment, exclude poor performers.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="search-terms-analysis">
      <p>The Search Terms report is the richest source of optimization insights. Go to Keywords → Search Terms, sort by cost (descending), and review each search:</p>
      <p><term name="Relevant and converting">Add as a new keyword (exact match if proven, phrase if exploratory).</term></p>
      <p><term name="Relevant but not converting">Monitor; may need landing page or offer improvements.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Irrelevant but high cost">Add as negative keyword immediately to stop wasted spend.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Irrelevant but low cost">Still add as negative to prevent future escalation.</term></p>
      <p>Weekly routine: export Search Terms, filter by cost &gt; $5, add negatives for irrelevant searches, add new keywords for valuable ones.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="optimization-actions">
      <p>When metrics deviate from target, follow this diagnostic tree:</p>
      <p><term name="Low impressions">Increase budget, broaden keywords, or raise bids. Likely causes: insufficient budget or targeting too narrow.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Low CTR">Improve ad headlines, test new ad variations, or ensure ad copy matches search intent. Cause: ads don't resonate.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Low Quality Score">Tighten ad groups to match keywords more closely, improve landing page relevance, increase CTR through better ads.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Low conversion rate">Optimize landing pages, improve offer clarity, ensure targeting matches landing page promise. Cause: landing page mismatch.</term></p>
      <p><term name="High CPA">Add negatives to reduce irrelevant traffic, reduce bids on poor performers, improve quality, tighten targeting. Cause: multiple factors.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Low impression share">Increase daily budget or raise bids. Likely causes: budget constraints or bid too low.</term></p>
    </section>
    <section name="reporting-schedule">
      <p>Establish a cadence for campaign management:</p>
      <p><term name="Daily (5 min)">Check spend pacing against daily budget, look for anomalies, ensure no ads are disapproved.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Weekly (30 min)">Full performance review across all campaigns, Search Terms analysis, add negatives, make bid adjustments, review Quality Scores.</term></p>
      <p><term name="Monthly (1 hour)">Trend analysis across full month, budget reallocation across campaigns, strategy assessment, test new features or creatives.</term></p>
    </section>
    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Never optimize based on clicks or impressions alone. Focus on conversion metrics (CPA, ROAS, conversions) to align optimization with business outcomes.</statement>
        <rationale>More clicks or impressions do not guarantee more conversions; vanity metrics can lead to budget waste.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Do not ignore the Search Terms report. New irrelevant searches accumulate weekly and burn budget; review it at least weekly.</statement>
        <rationale>Search Terms is the earliest signal of wasted spend and new keyword opportunities.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Avoid over-optimizing or making major changes daily. Limit major restructures to monthly cycles; day-to-day noise resets learning.</statement>
        <rationale>Google's learning algorithms need stability; constant churn prevents the system from reaching stability.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Focusing on the wrong metrics: clicks, impressions, or CTR instead of conversions and CPA.</description>
        <reason>More clicks at high CPA is worse than fewer clicks at low CPA; track metrics that tie to business outcomes.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Not segmenting data. Looking only at campaign-level averages hides high-performing and low-performing subsets.</description>
        <reason>Segment analysis reveals optimization opportunities missed at the aggregate level.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/weekly-checklist.md" purpose="Weekly optimization checklist: performance review, Search Terms actions, bid adjustments, next week priorities."/>
      <template path="templates/performance-report.md" purpose="Monthly performance report template with summary, campaign breakdown, top keywords, and recommendations."/>
      <template path="templates/weekly-report.py" purpose="Python script to generate automated weekly reports from Google Ads API data."/>
    </templates>
